      ---------------------------------------------------------
       Elastic APM integration testing with Docker Compose
      ---------------------------------------------------------


1. Overview
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This directory contains a Docker Compose setup for integration testing of the
OTel C wrapper library against an Elastic APM backend.  The stack consists of
Elasticsearch, Kibana, and APM Server.

OTLP Endpoints (APM Server):
  http://localhost:8200/v1/traces
  http://localhost:8200/v1/metrics
  http://localhost:8200/v1/logs

Web interfaces:
  Kibana:        http://localhost:5601
  Elasticsearch: http://localhost:9200


2. Prerequisites
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Docker Engine and Docker Compose (V2) must be installed.  All container images
are pulled from the official Elastic Docker registry.

The Elastic Stack version and passwords are configured in the .env file.
Edit the file before starting the stack if you need to change the defaults.

The es-init.sh script is not part of the Docker Compose workflow.  It is a
standalone reference script that can be run on the host to manually reset the
kibana_system and apm_system passwords in Elasticsearch via the REST API,
should the built-in password setup fail.


3. Starting the stack
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  % cd test/elastic-apm
  % docker compose up -d

Elasticsearch starts first.  Once its healthcheck passes, Kibana and APM Server
start in parallel.  The kibana-startup.sh script waits until the kibana_system
credentials are valid before launching Kibana.

To follow the startup progress:

  % docker compose logs -f

Wait until all three containers report healthy status:

  % docker compose ps


4. Running the test program
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ensure that the otel-cfg.yml configuration file points to the APM Server
endpoint (http://localhost:8200) and then run the test program:

  % ./otel-c-wrapper-test --runcount=10 --threads=8

Traces, metrics, and logs should appear in Kibana under the APM section.


5. Stopping the stack
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To stop all containers without removing volumes:

  % docker compose stop

To stop and remove containers, networks, and the named volume:

  % docker compose down -v


6. Uninstalling
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

After stopping and removing the containers, remove the pulled images:

  % docker compose down -v --rmi all

This removes the containers, the named volume, and all images pulled by the
compose file.
